{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13954"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13954"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.05,0.06,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56859"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6584"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42312"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2187"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"3730"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44986"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56859"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her parents for a routine check-up. She has a medical history of acute lymphoblastic leukaemia, diagnosed two years ago for which she is currently on maintenance therapy. Her current medications include daily oral mercaptopurine and weekly oral methotrexate. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her parents ask about updating her vaccinations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vaccines is contraindicated in this child?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine","Inactivated influenza vaccine","Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine","Diphtheria, tetanus, and acellular pertussis (DTaP) vaccine","Hepatitis B vaccine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated. The MMR vaccine is a live attenuated vaccine, which should not be administered to patients who are immunocompromised, such as children on maintenance therapy for acute leukaemia. Live vaccines contain weakened but still viable pathogens that could potentially cause infection in individuals with weakened immune systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einactivated influenza vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended for immunocompromised patients, including those with leukaemia. It contains killed virus particles and cannot cause infection, making it safe for use in this population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumococcal conjugate vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is also recommended for immunocompromised patients. It is not a live vaccine and helps protect against invasive pneumococcal disease, which these patients are at higher risk of developing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ediphtheria, tetanus, and acellular pertussis (DTaP) vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is an inactivated vaccine and is safe for use in immunocompromised patients. It\u0027s important to maintain protection against these diseases in all children, including those with leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis B vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is a recombinant vaccine that does not contain live virus. It is safe and recommended for immunocompromised patients, including those with leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn general, inactivated, recombinant, subunit, and toxoid vaccines are safe for use in immunocompromised patients. However, the immune response to these vaccines may be suboptimal. Live vaccines, such as MMR, varicella, rotavirus, oral polio vaccine, and live attenuated influenza vaccine, are contraindicated in severely immunocompromised patients due to the risk of vaccine-associated disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Live attenuated vaccines are contraindicated in children on maintenance therapy for acute leukaemia due to their immunocompromised state.","Other live attenuated vaccines to avoid in immunocompromised patients include varicella, rotavirus, and live attenuated influenza vaccines."],"references":["Sung L, Heurter H, Zokvic KM, Ford-Jones EL, Weitzman SS, Freeman R, Dupuis LL, Scheifele DW. Practical vaccination guidelines for children with cancer. Paediatr Child Health. 2001 Jul;6(6):379-83. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20084264/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42312"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13954"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42312"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T10:05:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T10:06:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6584"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56859"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https